    "body": "@jntrnr  You are punishing users for no reason. Even the **default-generated** `env.nu` and `config.nu` were broken. That is to say, users' applications were broken without their doing anything.\r\n\r\n```\r\n❯ nu\r\nError: nu::shell::deprecated_command\r\n\r\n  × Deprecated command let-env\r\n    ╭─[/Users/carter/Library/Application Support/nushell/env.nu:21:1]\r\n 21 │ # Use nushell functions to define your right and left prompt\r\n 22 │ let-env PROMPT_COMMAND = { create_left_prompt }\r\n    · ───┬───\r\n    ·    ╰── 'let-env' is deprecated. Please use '$env.<environment variable> = ...' instead.\r\n 23 │ let-env PROMPT_COMMAND_RIGHT = { create_right_prompt }\r\n    ╰────\r\n\r\nError: nu::shell::deprecated_command\r\n\r\n  × Deprecated command let-env\r\n     ╭─[/Users/carter/Library/Application Support/nushell/config.nu:185:1]\r\n 185 │ # The default config record. This is where much of your global configuration is setup.\r\n 186 │ let-env config = {\r\n     · ───┬───\r\n     ·    ╰── 'let-env' is deprecated. Please use '$env.<environment variable> = ...' instead.\r\n 187 │   # true or false to enable or disable the welcome banner at startup\r\n     ╰────\r\n```\r\n\r\nI'm not saying the change was bad. Since the change was expected to break most of people, you should give users and 3rd-party-tool developers some time to migrate their configurations by supporting both syntaxes.",
    "author_association": "NONE",
