    "created_at": "2023-07-27T05:53:35Z",
    "updated_at": "2023-07-27T06:01:53Z",
    "body": "> we did announce the plans to remove let-env more than three weeks ago, and also reached out to third-party tools to make sure they had updates. That said, I think where we could have done better is to make sure tool maintainers knew when the Nushell version without let-env was shipping.\r\n\r\nIt doesn't make sense. You announce the plans to remove `let-env`, then what? Let 3rd-party-tool developers change `let-env` to `$env.` like what the error messages said?\r\n\r\nNo, they can't, since nushell 0.83 is not released yet. Even if nushell 0.83 is released, there are people can't upgrade it, because, you know, the chaotic *nix package management system of different distros. In the end, they have to find a way to resolve the incompatibilty between 0.82 and 0.83, and that is definitely not as easy as changing `let-env` to `$env.`\r\n\r\nAnd what if the 3rd-party tool can't cut a release in time, or it's not maintained anymore? As long as one link is not right, users' application will be broken, and they can't do anything but wait.\r\n\r\nIt's not 3rd-party-tool developers' fault. It's your fault. And even if it's 3rd-party-tool developers' fault, you are not punishing the developers. You ARE punishing users.",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "pin": null,
